            <h2>City of Santa Rosa</h2>
            <h3>The Lion City of South Luzon</h3>
            <hr>
            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfSantaRosa1.png" alt="">
            <p>Santa Rosa is named from the first patron saint of South America, Santa Rosa de Lima of Peru. It became a municipality on January 18, 1792 from a mere barrio of Biñan called Barrio Bukol. During the revolutionary period, Santa Rosa signed the Act of Independence from Spain on June 12, 1898. The local leaders fought alongside General Emilio Aguinaldo during the Filipino-American War. After a brief occupation by the Japanese forces during the Second World War, the town was liberated on February 5, 1945.</p>
            <p>During the post war era, Santa Rosa’s local economy was depen- dent on farming, fishing, livestock and small backyard industry. Industrialization came in the 1980’s with the entry of foreign multinational companies in economic zones and industrial estates.</p>
            <p>From a fourth-class municipality in 1986, Santa Rosa became a first-class town in 1993, and officially became the 101st city in the Philippines on July 10, 2004.</p>
            <p>Today, the City of Santa Rosa is living up to its symbol – the lion. Its economy is vibrant and booming, and so to speak, roaring like a lion.</p>
            <p>As The Lion City of South Luzon, Santa Rosa is the headquarters to some of the major corporations in the Philippines. These include the largest bottling plant of Coca-Cola in the Far East and the manufacturing plant of food giant Monde Nissin Corp.</p>
            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>
            <ol><li>1. The major festival is the Sikhayan Festival, which is celebrated every January 18, coinciding with Santa Rosa’s founding anniversary as a separate and independent town in the Laguna Province.
                    Short for SikapKabuhayan, Sikhayan is a celebration of life, a tribute to the people’s unrelenting and resolute effort, to their profound sense of community, to their deeply rooted cultural heritage, and to their enterprising spirit.
                </li><li>2. The City’s major destinations include: Enchanted Kingdom (the Philippines’ first and only world-class theme park), Cuartel de Santo Domingo (a Spanish-era fort, the city’s version of Intramuros), Nuvali-Solenad (One of the city’s most modern, eco-friendly business, and commercial complex) and Paseo de Santa Rosa (A shopper’s haven, night time is the best time to visit) and City Proper (See the city’s rich cultural heritage)
                </li></ol>

